In June 2018, the BAE design was selected, with an initial order of 30 ACVs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.defenseone.com/business/2018/06/marines-buy-new-amphibious-combat-vehicle-bae-systems/149141 |title=Marines to Buy New Amphibious Combat Vehicle from BAE Systems |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=19 June 2018 |website=defenseone.com |publisher= |access-date= }}</ref> In June 2019, BAE Systems and Iveco were awarded a contract to develop Command and 30mm gun armed variants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ukdefencejournal.org.uk/us-marine-corps-awards-bae-contract-for-acv-family-of-vehicles/?no_cache=1|title = US Marine Corps awards BAE contract for ACV family of vehicles|date = 27 June 2019}}</ref>

In October 2020, Iveco announced that the first fleet of 18 ACVs had been delivered to a platoon of Marines after five years of testing development.<ref name="armyrecognition.com"/>

In December 2020, the Marine Corps and BAE Systems announced the commencement of full-rate production, with an initial batch of 36, expected to grow to 72 in early 2021, with an option for 80 vehicles per year thereafter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defensenews.com/land/2020/12/10/marine-corps-amphibious-combat-vehicle-reaches-full-rate-production/|title = US Marine Corps' amphibious combat vehicle reaches full-rate production|date = 14 December 2020}}</ref> The subcontract for the ACV's remote turret went to [[Kongsberg Defence Systems]] with the [[Protector (RWS)|Protector RT20]].<ref>[https://www.kongsberg.com/no/kda/products/defence-and-security/remote-weapon-systems/protector-rt20/ "PROTECTOR RT20"]. kongsberg.com</ref>

A January 2021 report from the Department of Defense's Director of Operational Test & Evaluation (DOT&E) pointed to several problems with the ACV, including cramped quarters, difficult egress and frequent breakdown.<ref>{{Cite web|date=January 2021|title=Amphibious Combat Vehicle Family of Vehicles|url=https://www.dote.osd.mil/Portals/97/pub/reports/FY2020/navy/2020acv.pdf|access-date=January 26, 2021|website=Director, Operational Test and Evaluation}}</ref>

In August 2022, the U.S. Marine Corps awarded BAE Systems an $88 million contract to build multiple ACV-30 Production Representative Test Vehicles (PRTVs).<ref>{{Cite web|date=August 15, 2022|title=BAE Systems receives $88 million contract for ACV-30 test vehicles|url=https://www.baesystems.com/en/article/bae-systems-receives-88-million-contract-for-acv-30-test-vehicles|access-date=August 31, 2022|website=BAE systems}}</ref>

== Variants ==
The ACV Family of Vehicles is made of what was initially, the ACV 1.1 and ACV 1.2. 
* ACV 1.1: it was designed with the requirement for a swim capability of at least 3 nautical miles from its ship to the shore.<ref name=":7">{{Cite web |last=Parsons |first=Dan |date=2018-04-27 |title=Testing Complete, Marines To Choose Amphibious Combat Vehicle In June |url=https://www.defensedaily.com/testing-complete-marines-choose-amphibious-combat-vehicle-june/navy-usmc/ |access-date=2024-04-29 |website=Defense Daily |language=en-US}}</ref>
* ACV 1.2: The requirement for its capability is set to be increased to 12 miles from the ship to the shore, and additional improvements are expected to be made. Communication and recovery variants are also expected.<ref name=":7" />

Both generations were merged to make a common basis for various variants in January 2019.<ref name=":33">{{Cite web |date=December 2022 |title=Selected Acquisition Report (SAR) |url=https://www.esd.whs.mil/Portals/54/Documents/FOID/Reading%20Room/Selected_Acquisition_Reports/FY_2022_SARS/ACV%20FoV_SAR_DEC_2022_final.pdf |access-date=October 19, 2024 |website=www.esd.whs.mil}}</ref>

=== Variants in production and in service ===

==== ACV-C ====
[[File:Amphibious Combat Vehicle Command (ACV-C).jpg|thumb|right|ACV-C]]

The Amphibious Combat Vehicle – Command and Control (ACV-C) is a variant of the ACV designed to serve as a mobile command post. It shares the same hull, powertrain, drivetrain, and survivability suite as the ACV-P (Personnel variant) but is equipped with seven radios, additional antennas, and an expanded battery pack to support silent watch operations. The vehicle enables secure voice and data communications, supports operational planning, intelligence processing, fire support coordination, and logistics management.<ref>{{Cite web |last=U.S. Navy |date=2022 |title=Amphibious Combat Vehicle – Command and Control variant (ACV-C) |url=https://www.dote.osd.mil/Portals/97/pub/reports/FY2022/navy/2022acv-c.pdf?ver=ZktVYKG6t7TmUPlHgemvLA%3D%3D |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250312144659/https://www.dote.osd.mil/Portals/97/pub/reports/FY2022/navy/2022acv-c.pdf?ver=ZktVYKG6t7TmUPlHgemvLA%3D%3D |archive-date=12 March 2025 |access-date=22 March 2025}}</ref>

The first production vehicle of this variant was delivered in January 2024.<ref name=":4" /> It has an AAO (approved acquisition objective) of 33 vehicles.<ref name=":8">{{Cite web |title=FAVS 2023: US Marines to deploy ACV amphibious vehicles in 2024 |url=https://www.janes.com/defence-news/news-detail/favs-2023-us-marines-to-deploy-acv-amphibious-vehicles-in-2024 |access-date=2024-04-29 |website=Janes.com |date=17 November 2023 |language=en}}</ref>

==== ACV-P ====
The ACV-P is the personnel carrier variant of the ACV. It carries a crew of three and can transport a squad of thirteen Marines, along with two days' worth of combat equipment and supplies.<ref name=":6" /> The ACV-P is equipped with the [[M153|M153 Protector Remote Weapon Station]] (RWS), which can be fitted with either the [[M2 .50 Caliber Machine Gun|M2 .50 Caliber machine gun]], ready to fire with 400 rounds, or a [[Mk 19 grenade launcher|Mk-19]] grenade launcher, ready to fire with 96 rounds.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Maj Justin Davis |date=February 2021 |title=Go All In The Marine Corps guide to maximizing the ACV |url=https://www.mca-marines.org/wp-content/uploads/53-Go-All-In.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250322164028/https://www.mca-marines.org/wp-content/uploads/53-Go-All-In.pdf |archive-date=22 March 2025 |access-date=22 March 2025}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2017-01-31 |title=Weapon system moves Reserve gunners to the safety of the backseat |url=https://www.army.mil/article/181552/weapon_system_moves_reserve_gunners_to_the_safety_of_the_backseat |access-date=2025-03-22 |website=www.army.mil |language=en}}</ref> The M153 is a stabilized mount that contains a sensor suite and fire control software. It allows on-the-move target acquisition and first-burst target engagement. Capable of target engagement under day and night conditions, the M153's sensor suite includes a daytime video camera, thermal camera and laser rangefinder.<ref>{{Cite web |title=PEO Soldier |url=https://www.peosoldier.army.mil/Equipment/Equipment-Portfolio/Project-Manager-Soldier-Lethality-Portfolio/M153-A1-A2-CROWS/ |access-date=2025-01-23 |website=www.peosoldier.army.mil}}{{source-attribution}}</ref> The ACV-P has an AAO (approved acquisition objective) of 390 vehicles, it reached its IOC in 2020.<ref name=":8" />

